    "SOURCE: https://www.gsma.com/solutions-and-impact/connectivity-for-good/mobile-for-development/programme/mobile-money/addressing-the-financial-services-needs-of-msmes-in-sub-saharan-africa/ KB: kb8_national_policy_strategy Addressing the financial services needs of MSMEs in Sub-Saharan Africa | Mobile for Development Home ... Mobile for Development Addressing the financial services needs of MSMEs in Sub-Saharan Africa Monday 18 February, 2019 (modified Monday 24 November, 2025) Addressing the fi",
    "in Sub-Saharan Africa Monday 18 February, 2019 (modified Monday 24 November, 2025) Addressing the financial services needs of MSMEs in Sub-Saharan Africa Like what you read? Share. Opportunity presented by Enterprise customers In a previous blog, we highlighted how mobile money still remains largely focused on individual customers with over 99% of registered accounts owned by individuals. However, Enterprise customers represent a large and untapped opportunity for mobile money providers. To bett",
    "Enterprise customers represent a large and untapped opportunity for mobile money providers. To better understand the needs of MSMEs in Sub-Saharan Africa and how mobile money operators can best address their financial needs, the GSMA Mobile Money team partnered up with two leading consulting firms and operators over the past year to conduct two studies. What MSMEs need To assess the pain-points and financial services needs of MSMEs, GSMA partnered with Sofrecom and a leading mobile money operat",
    "nd financial services needs of MSMEs, GSMA partnered with Sofrecom and a leading mobile money operator to conduct quantitative and qualitative research on the topic in a Central African country with a thriving mobile money industry. We found that MSMEs operate in a rich ecosystem, engage in diversified interactions with suppliers, providers and public authorities, and conduct frequent transactions . While cash is the most common payment mode, its use tends to decrease when the transaction size i",
    ". While cash is the most common payment mode, its use tends to decrease when the transaction size increases. Despite being tailored for individual needs, mobile money ranked as the 2nd payment mode and is already used by more than 80% of respondents for professional purpose (figure 1). The most frequent business use-cases include accepting customer payments and paying providers and suppliers. Mobile Money is valued for the proximity and service of its agents and for the flexibility and ease of",
    "ile Money is valued for the proximity and service of its agents and for the flexibility and ease of processing a payment. On average, nearly 60% of the respondents face working capital issues . Businesses struggle to manage cash tensions as there is a lack of savings and access to credit is complicated, especially at formal financial institutions. It is understood that these difficulties are the main reason for them seeking loans, while investment is less-often mentioned by enterprises surveyed.",
    "ain reason for them seeking loans, while investment is less-often mentioned by enterprises surveyed. According to the McKinsey Global Institute at least 200 million MSMEs in emerging economies have no or insufficient access to credit, blocking their growth. In Africa, over 50% of MSMEs are unserved or underserved, accounting for 35m MSMEs and a $528b credit gap. These numbers would be even higher if they took into account the large number of informal businesses active in the continent[1]. 70% of",
    "if they took into account the large number of informal businesses active in the continent[1]. 70% of respondents to Sofrecom’s survey claimed receiving credit through informal channels , which are valued for the minimal guarantee requirements and the flexibility offered. The pain-points of online MSMEs Prior to this, in 2017 the Mobile Money team partnered with Dalberg Design and a leading Mobile Money Operator in Western Africa, to assess the pain-points and needs of online MSMEs. Dalberg Desig",
    "Money Operator in Western Africa, to assess the pain-points and needs of online MSMEs. Dalberg Design used a combination of research and prototyping methods, engaging over 50 participants to outline the journey of online MSMEs. This would typically involve five steps: Online set-up of the business; receiving an order; organizing a delivery; order acceptance; and potential returns/ product exchanges. While pain-points would typically differ according to merchant type (small merchant vs. online ve",
    "s. While pain-points would typically differ according to merchant type (small merchant vs. online vendors) there are a common set of challenges for online MSMEs which include: lack of set-up support to build websites and integrate digital payment solutions; and non-existent tracking tools for delivery, payment and refunds. Furthermore, online MSMEs are ill-equipped to make refunds and there is a lack of clarity on customer support and liability in case of losses/ refunds. Mobile Money providers",
    "ack of clarity on customer support and liability in case of losses/ refunds. Mobile Money providers can help to address these needs A large number of payment providers such as Ant Financial, Mercado Libre and MasterCard have designed dedicated value propositions and have already launched innovative initiatives targeting MSMEs by providing access to credit. While just a few mobile money players have developed a tailored offering for businesses, this is perceived as a strong opportunity by the ind",
    "e developed a tailored offering for businesses, this is perceived as a strong opportunity by the industry and 49 per cent of mobile money providers participating in our Global Adoption Survey cited enterprise solutions as one of their top three strategic priorities for 2018. Mobile money providers are well-placed to serve MSMEs thanks to their strong-presence on the ground. While most mobile money providers seem to be at an early stage of specifically addressing MSMEs needs, a large number of fo",
    "providers seem to be at an early stage of specifically addressing MSMEs needs, a large number of formal and informal MSMEs is already using mobile money for business purposes. Mobile money providers are therefore ideally positioned to capitalise on the opportunity in emerging markets and provide tailored offerings for MSMEs that can help to reduce their pain points and support further digitisation of the economy. Read the report [1] McKinsey Global Institute, September 2016, Digital Finance for",
    "n of the economy. Read the report [1] McKinsey Global Institute, September 2016, Digital Finance for all: Powering inclusive growth in emerging economies. You may be interested in Tuesday 26 May, 2026 How Jio is improving handset affordability and access for the underserved in India Read article Sunday 24 May, 2026 Connected when it counts: Mobile-enabled early warning systems for island nations Read article Like what you read? Share.",
    "FULIZA M-PESA — OVERDRAFT FACILITY GUIDE ========================================= What is Fuliza? Fuliza is a Safaricom M-PESA overdraft service that allows you to complete M-PESA transactions even when you have insufficient funds in your M-PESA wallet. Who Qualifies for Fuliza? - Active Safaricom M-PESA user for at least 6 months - Regular M-PESA transaction history - Good repayment history on previous loans - Limit is determined by your M-PESA usage history How to Activate Fuliza: 1. Dial *23",
    "revious loans - Limit is determined by your M-PESA usage history How to Activate Fuliza: 1. Dial *234# on your Safaricom line 2. Select \"Fuliza M-PESA\" 3. Select \"Activate\" 4. Accept terms and conditions 5. Your limit will be displayed How Fuliza Works for Business: - If you need to pay a supplier but have insufficient funds - Fuliza covers the shortfall automatically during the transaction - Repayment is deducted from your next M-PESA deposit - Daily maintenance fee applies on outstanding balan",
    "yment is deducted from your next M-PESA deposit - Daily maintenance fee applies on outstanding balance Fuliza Charges: - Access fee: 1% of amount borrowed (minimum KES 2) - Daily maintenance fee: Based on outstanding amount - No interest if repaid on same day Fuliza Limits: - Minimum: KES 100 - Maximum: Based on your M-PESA usage and creditworthiness - Limits reviewed regularly based on usage Important for MSMEs: - Use Fuliza only for short-term cash flow gaps - Repay quickly to avoid daily main",
    "rtant for MSMEs: - Use Fuliza only for short-term cash flow gaps - Repay quickly to avoid daily maintenance fees - Higher M-PESA usage may increase your Fuliza limit - Available 24/7 automatically during transactions Contact: Safaricom 100 or safaricom.co.ke",
    "POCHI LA BIASHARA — SAFARICOM OFFICIAL GUIDE ============================================= What is Pochi La Biashara? Pochi La Biashara is a free Safaricom M-PESA service that allows small business owners to receive business payments directly to their existing M-PESA registered phone number, while keeping business funds separate from personal funds. Key Benefits: - Separate business and personal M-PESA funds on the same line - No need for a separate business line or till number - Free to registe",
    "-PESA funds on the same line - No need for a separate business line or till number - Free to register and use - Customers pay using your phone number directly - Access business funds anytime How to Register for Pochi La Biashara: Method 1 — Via USSD: 1. Dial *334# from your Safaricom M-PESA registered line 2. Select \"Pochi La Biashara\" 3. Select \"Join Pochi\" 4. Choose your business category 5. Accept terms and conditions 6. Registration is complete — you will receive a confirmation SMS Method 2",
    "ept terms and conditions 6. Registration is complete — you will receive a confirmation SMS Method 2 — Via M-PESA Super App: 1. Open the M-PESA Super App on your smartphone 2. Select \"Pay\" 3. Select \"Pochi La Biashara\" 4. Enter the merchant phone number 5. Enter amount and confirm Method 3 — Via MySafaricom App: 1. Open MySafaricom App 2. Go to M-PESA 3. Select Pochi La Biashara 4. Follow registration steps How Customers Pay You via Pochi La Biashara: 1. Customer dials *334# or opens M-PESA Super",
    "ion steps How Customers Pay You via Pochi La Biashara: 1. Customer dials *334# or opens M-PESA Super App 2. Selects \"Send Money\" or \"Pay\" 3. Selects \"Pochi La Biashara\" 4. Enters your registered phone number 5. Enters amount 6. Confirms payment 7. Both you and customer receive SMS confirmation Accessing Your Pochi La Biashara Funds: - Dial *334# and select Pochi La Biashara to check balance - Transfer funds to your M-PESA wallet anytime - Withdraw from any M-PESA agent Business Categories Availa",
    "sfer funds to your M-PESA wallet anytime - Withdraw from any M-PESA agent Business Categories Available: - Retail shop / Duka - Food and beverages - Clothing and fashion - Electronics - Hardware - Agriculture - Services (salon, repair, etc.) - Transport - Other Pochi La Biashara vs Other Payment Options: - Pochi La Biashara: Uses your phone number, free, for small businesses - M-PESA Till Number (Buy Goods): Requires application, has monthly fees, for larger businesses - M-PESA Paybill: For busi",
    "Buy Goods): Requires application, has monthly fees, for larger businesses - M-PESA Paybill: For businesses needing account references, monthly fees apply Important Notes: - Must have an active M-PESA account to register - Must be a Safaricom subscriber - Available for individuals and small businesses - No monthly charges for Pochi La Biashara - Transaction limits follow standard M-PESA limits For support: Call Safaricom on 100 or visit any Safaricom shop Website: safaricom.co.ke",
    "support: Call Safaricom on 100 or visit any Safaricom shop Website: safaricom.co.ke",
