    "unty governments? PAGE 2 PAGE 3 PAGE 5 DISCLAIMER: The information contained in this publication is meant as a basic informational guide about the Kenya Roads Board (KRB) and does not remove the need to seek further help from the KRB team. Who is the Kenya Roads Board? The Kenya Roads Board (KRB) is a State Corporation maintenance, rehabilitation and development of these established under KRB ACT No. 7, of 1999 to oversee infrastructure through the KRB Fund and also advises the road network in K",
    "No. 7, of 1999 to oversee infrastructure through the KRB Fund and also advises the road network in Kenya. The Board coordinates the the Minister for Transport on all matters related thereto. Is KRB the same as Explain KeNHA, KeNHA or KURA? KURA, KeRRA... Not. Besides playing an oversight role over KeNHA, The agencies were established in 2007, through the KURA, KeRRA, the Board is also responsible for funding Kenya Roads Act. They make up three of four pillars (2,3 these the road agencies. It doe",
    "for funding Kenya Roads Act. They make up three of four pillars (2,3 these the road agencies. It does this using the Road &4) identified in the 1980s by the Road Maintenance Maintenance Levy Fund (RMLF). The Kenya Wildlife Initiative, a component of the Sub-Saharan Africa Service (KWS) also gets a share of the RMLF to develop Transport Programme supported by the World Bank, and maintain roads in national parks and game reserves. as key to reversing deteriorating road network. Kenya Roads Board f",
    "ational parks and game reserves. as key to reversing deteriorating road network. Kenya Roads Board fulfils pillars 1,2 and 3. 2 Quick infobytes What determines the amount allocated to each agency? The KRB Act provides for the allocation of funds to the Road Agencies. KeNHA receives 40 per cent, KeRRA 25 per cent, KURA 15 per cent and Kenya Wildlife Service 1 per cent of the Fund. The Board reviews annual road work plans submitted by the Road Agencies and consolidates them into the Annual Public",
    "annual road work plans submitted by the Road Agencies and consolidates them into the Annual Public Roads Programme (APRP) which outlines the planned road works and specifies the amount allocated to each. What numbers are we talking about in the FY2021/22? In the FY 2021-2022, KeNHA (Classes S, A & B) will receive Sh26,592,551,020, and KeRRA (Class C) Ksh. 14, 590,870,343. KURA (Urban Roads Classes UA, UB & UC) and KWS (Roads within National Parks and Game Reserves) has been allocated Kshs. 6,65",
    "s UA, UB & UC) and KWS (Roads within National Parks and Game Reserves) has been allocated Kshs. 6,651,970,473 and Kshs. 651,338,776 respectively Tell us about the Road Maintenance Levy The Fund was established through the Road Maintenance Levy Fund (RMLF) Act of 1993 to provide a sustainable source of funding for the maintenance of the road network. The fund has steadily grown from Sh8 billion in 2002 to over Sh80 billion today. Quick infobytes 3 And the Fuel Levy Fund? The KRB Fund comprises ma",
    "2002 to over Sh80 billion today. Quick infobytes 3 And the Fuel Levy Fund? The KRB Fund comprises mainly of fuel levy and transit Road Annuity Fund to upgrade 10,000km of roads with tolls. Fuel levy is a user-charge on petrol and diesel asphalt surfacing. Transit tolls are charged on transit at KSh18 per litre. Of this, Sh3 is applied towards the vehicles plying Kenyan roads. How effective has RMLF been over the years? Kenya’s classified road network has increased from 41,800 km at independence",
    "F been over the years? Kenya’s classified road network has increased from 41,800 km at independence to 63,575 km today, a development rate of no less than 600 km per annum. During the same period, the paved road length grew from 1,811 km to 9,273 km. It is presently estimated that about 70 per cent (44,100 km) of the classified road network is in good condition and is maintainable while the remaining 30 per cent (18,900 km) requires rehabilitation or reconstruction. Why are roads so important? T",
    "ing 30 per cent (18,900 km) requires rehabilitation or reconstruction. Why are roads so important? Transportation is a key driver of socio-economic growth in every country making infrastructure a key driver of any nation’s development. Good roads enable farmers and other producers to get their produce to the market and at less cost. Countries with the best roads make mobility and distribution of goods and services faster and easier. This goes a long way to improve the bottom line of companies an",
    "oods and services faster and easier. This goes a long way to improve the bottom line of companies and improves the country’s GDP. 4 Quick infobytes How does road classification work? It is the orderly grouping of roads and in Kenya, this over technical requirements and maintenance practices. can be administratively (National or County Roads) Kenya Roads Board undertakes road classification on and/or Functionally (Class A, B…. G). Administrative behalf of the Ministry of Transport, Infrastructure",
